sidney blumenthal   :    topic: political power of geert wilders in the netherlands         un u.s. department of state case no. f-- doc no. c :       un u.s. department of state case no. f-- doc no. c : the p government of the conservative party (vvd) and christian democrats (cda) is a minoritygovernment. to get a majority on the issues they consider important, they signed a contract with the pvv ofgeert wilders (party for fedom, partij voor de vrijheid). with this support they have a majority of one votein parliament.wilders gave his support in exchange for government support for his priorities: against islam and islamicpeople, against eu, against arts & cultu, no compassion with minorities, in favor of being tough on criminals,against the left, etc.in this spect it looks like (political) business as usual. but it isnt. wilders has a complete control on thegovernment, as without his support the coalition will no longer be in charge.from the diffent sources (a former prime minister ‰ÛÓ who is close to hm the queen, an acting dictorgeneral, and a former head of protocol to the vice prime minister) i have been told that prime minister andvice prime minister meet with mr. wilders once a week, they go through the list of issues and nominations,and he has to give his con on every topic that it is part of the agement between the coalition and mr.wilders. in practice this means that he has full control on all major political decisions and importantnominations. it is a brilliant position as he doesnt have to take the heat for being sponsible (as he is not in thegovernment but controls the government!).in practice it means that everybody with a leading position (including all civil servants) must keep in mind:"what does wilders want." the has developed a sphe of fear, self-censorship and censorship.to give a few examples: a candi for the dutch supme court was no longer allowed to be candi whenit became public that during the trial against wilders he had written a critical memo against wilders.as all public media a depending on government subsidies, youll not hear any critical voice against wilders ashe has make the that that financial support will be withdrawn. one of the tragicomic consequences is thatwhen wilders second man and party-ideologue, martin bosma, published his idiotic book in which he claimsthat hitler was a leftist, and so the leftliberals a the fascists, he ally could get away with all of thisnonse, as all talk shows complied to his demand that no other guest was allowed to come when he appead.one of the consequences is a kind of internalizing of "wilders-thinking" on all levels. as a sult the primeminister can say, after he wins gional elections: "finally we can give back the netherlands to the dutchpeople" (as at any time in the last decade this country no longer belonged to the dutch people). and the viceprime minister could make this argument: "i understand the worries of the dutch people. with foigners, youget foign food and with foign food foign diseases..."the biggest problem is that wilders and his neo-fascist ideas have become so much accepted, that indeed it hasbecome unacceptable to criticize him. brievik, the norwegian fascist and mass murder, mentions wildersover  times as his gat hero, example etc. wilders line of defense: "bivik is insane. i have nothing to dowith him. but sponsible for the acts of bivik a the muslims because they drove him to these actions...."the argument is absurd, but again, it is widely accepted.in the latest polls, however, he is losing a bit of support. this might be because wilders made one commentabout the queen, which was even for a majority of his voters too much. but it is way too soon to say that he isover the top. he is in control, he decides how long this cabinet is allowed to exist, and he has proven again andagain to be the most brilliant politician we have had in decades.      un u.s. department of state case no. f-- doc no. c :

(as an aside, its stunning that thetrade lationship between us amounts to about a billion a day in economic benefits for us and them. its a shame thatthis nafta achievement is not as well known as should be.) we will have several new collaborations coming out of thisand we working on a significant commitment from wal-mart.i had a good meeting with your friend the fm espinosa, she said she was very happy when she learned from others thatin my speech to the top women in business, i noted that as a young diplomat at the un, she was a key negotiator of thebeijing platform for action. she said she doubted anyone in mexico knew the role she had played. when i got to themeeting with her she spent a lot of time talking about the importance of beijing, your role and membering lots ofexperiences about how tough the negotiations we -- from the iranians to the vatican to her own delegation! sheally wants to get women and economy on g and wants us to help with tasury. she also wants a gater emphasison women in climate change and asked if we would join on that.she ages that the a many positive things we can work together on besides the partnership on ending drug violenceand drug trafficking and that we should put an emphasis on those, particularly given the close ties we have, also, theelections ion both countries will only exacerbate the negative. bill probably told you that the mexican pss thinkswe somehow undemining mexicos soveignty with some of our anti drug efforts and their ading too much intotony waynes coming in as new amb from a posting in afghanistan!i also met with their ag who perhaps has the toughest job of anyone trying to build up their justice system. you gave herthe iwoc award when she was still prosecutor. so many mentioned what that award meant for mexico and her and, sheespecially wanted to be membed to you,please give our good wishes to the birthday celebrant.im confident hell be laying off birthday cake.i hope you get some vacation, despite the state of the world.        un u.s. department of state case no. f-- doc no. c :

"you gave her a pass," he said. befo leaving, mr. ford told ms. conlin that if he chose torun he hoped to turn to ask for the groups support. ms. conlin sponded: "we can never support you if you takethese positions." mr. ford "looked shocked," a person in the room said.       un u.s. department of state case no. f-- doc no. c :      un u.s. department of state case no. f-- doc no. c : his meeting with gay rights advocates on feb.  was rockier still. when he walked into the headquarters of thestonewall democrats in the chelsea neighborhood of manhattan, he was geted by signs that ad "liar!" and "gohome snake oil harry," a fence to his cent support for gay marriage after having twice voted to outlaw it incongss.a few days later, the sults of a poll that mr. ford had paid for out of his own pocket began to trickle in, giving hisadvisers pause. his negative ratings had incased slightly. a liberal primary electorate seemed wary about portions ofhis cord. ms. gillibrand mained vulnerable, the a showed, but mr. fords chance seemed to be -.
